WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified memory profile for the JEDEC LPDDR6 and LPDDR6X standards.
It defines the data rate (10.7–14.4 Gbps per pin), the channel architecture
(48 bits per channel, 16‑bit sub‑channels, quad‑channel), the bandwidth
formula, the power efficiency (21% over LPDDR5), the maximum capacity
(512 GB via SOCAMM2), the latency characteristics, and the Processing‑
in‑Memory (PIM) capabilities. All parameters are expressed through
auditable formulas.

WHY IT EXISTS
LPDDR6 is the memory backbone of 2026 flagship smartphones (Snapdragon 8
Elite Gen 5, A19 Pro, Dimensity 9500, Exynos 2600) and is extending into
AI datacenters via SOCAMM2 and PIM. GIOP must model its bandwidth, latency,
and capacity as formulas to predict frame buffer transfer times, AI model
loading latency, and real‑time HDR video encoding throughput.

HOW IT WORKS
Data Rate and Clocking:
  LPDDR6: 10.7 Gbps to 14.4 Gbps per pin (JEDEC standard upper limit).
  LPDDR6X: 12.8 Gbps (Samsung), targeting 14.0 Gbps.
  Effective clock frequency (DDR):
    f_clock = f_data / 2
  At 14.4 Gbps, f_clock = 7.2 GHz.

Channel Architecture:
  Standard channel width: 48 bits (3 × 16‑bit sub‑channels).
  Each sub‑channel operates independently with its own command/address bus.
  Quad‑channel package: 4 × 48 bits = 192‑bit total width.

Bandwidth per Channel:
  BW_channel = (channel_width_bits * f_data * 2(DDR)) / 8 (bytes)
  For a 48‑bit channel at 14.4 Gbps:
    BW_channel = (48 * 14.4e9 * 2) / 8 = 172.8 GB/s
  For a quad‑channel package (192‑bit total):
    BW_package = 4 * 172.8 = 691.2 GB/s (peak theoretical).

Bandwidth per Device (typical smartphone, 64‑bit):
  Many smartphones use a 64‑bit interface (2 × 32‑bit or 4 × 16‑bit).
    BW_device = (64 * 14.4e9 * 2) / 8 = 86.4 GB/s (at maximum 14.4 Gbps).

Bandwidth per Package (SOCAMM2, 256‑bit AI module):
    BW_SOCAMM2 = (256 * 14.4e9 * 2) / 8 = 921.6 GB/s.

Impact on Imaging Workloads:
  8K 60 fps HDR RAW (16‑bit float, 3 channels):
    Data_rate = 7680 * 4320 * 60 * 6 = 11.9 GB/s
    This is ~13.8% of a 86.4 GB/s device bandwidth.
  8K 60 fps HDR encode (VVC, 4:2:0 10‑bit):
    Data_rate (read+write) ≈ 2 GB/s, under 3% of bandwidth.
  AI inference (Stable Diffusion XL, 3.5 B parameters, FP8):
    Model weights: ~3.5 GB. Load time at 86.4 GB/s ≈ 40 ms.
    Activation memory (batch 1, 1024×1024): ~2 GB. Transfer ≈ 23 ms.

Power Efficiency:
  Active power:
    P_active = C_load * V_dd^2 * f_data * utilization
  V_dd = 1.05 V (LPDDR6) vs 1.1 V (LPDDR5).
  C_load typical: ~2.5 pF per pin.
  At 14.4 Gbps, 100% utilization, single 16‑bit sub‑channel:
    P_active ≈ 2.5e-12 * 1.05^2 * 14.4e9 ≈ 40 mW.
  Total device power (4 sub‑channels fully active): ~160 mW (logic + I/O).
  Power efficiency improvement: 21% over LPDDR5 at equivalent bandwidth
  (JEDEC).
  Self‑refresh power: <0.5 mW per Gb.
  Deep power‑down: <0.1 mW per device.

Processing‑in‑Memory (PIM):
  LPDDR6 introduces an optional PIM standard.
  PIM operations: ADD, MUL, MAC (multiply‑accumulate) directly in the
  memory bank, reducing data movement over the memory bus.
  MAC throughput per bank (FP16):
    MACs_per_bank = 16 * f_mem_clock
    At 7.2 GHz memory clock, 16 MACs per bank → 115 GFLOPS per bank.
    For a 16‑bank device: up to 1.84 TFLOPS on‑die FP16.
  PIM reduces energy for AI inference by up to 60% compared to off‑chip
  DRAM → NPU transfer, because the weight matrix never leaves memory.
  GIOP can target LPDDR6‑PIM by dispatching LMT weight‑matrix operations
  as PIM MAC commands.

Latency Model:
  Row Activation: t_RCD = 18 ns.
  Column Access: t_CL = 22 ns (at 14.4 Gbps).
  Read Latency (first word): t_RL = t_RCD + t_CL ≈ 40 ns.
  Subsequent words in burst: 1 word per 0.14 ns (BL16 = 2.2 ns).
  Precharge: t_RP = 18 ns.
  Sustained sequential read throughput: >90% of peak BW.

Capacity:
  Single die: 16 Gb (2 GB) at 14.4 Gbps (SK Hynix, ISSCC 2026).
  Max package capacity: up to 512 GB via 8‑high stacked dies and
  SOCAMM2 modules for AI datacenter applications.
  Mobile SoC (PoP): up to 24 GB with 4‑high stacks.

GIOP Runtime Implications:
  The GIOP runtime must query the LPDDR6 bandwidth to schedule
  concurrent read/write operations. For video encoding, the runtime
  SHALL ensure that:
    BW_available >= BW_read + BW_write + BW_AI_inference
  When total demand exceeds 80% of peak BW, the runtime SHALL throttle
  background AI tasks (e.g., auto‑tagging) to avoid frame drops.

